text: What a great day for aviation.  Sully is a hero.         However, you would assume that the depiction of it by Hollywood would be down to the detail since we have all the ATC tapes.  It would have been clearly possible for Hanks to use the exact same words as Sully used in the cockpit, but the script varies from it.  I've only seen the trailer of a couple of minutes and there are a number of mistakes, the most glaring of which is that in the movie,  ATC clears them for takeoff on the wrong runway at LGA, runway 4.  In fact they were cleared for and took off on runway 31.  Other documentaries have it right.  One wonders how they got that wrong especially since Sully was there to correct them.  AMAZING!

text: The pilot is a legend. He landed the plane in the Hudson, everyone was alive. Had he decided to land on any other airport, he would have crashed on the runway or on buildings; the NTSB is an idiotic bunch to say that he took a wrong decision. A good pilot deserves respect; it's very easy to sit and boast, but not that easy to fly a giant metal tube at 900 kmph, where anything can go wrong at any second, given the sophistication level of the hydraulics, computers and what not. Kudos to all military and commercial pilots, and to the engineers and technicians who build aeroplanes.

Virtually all planes that ditch in the sea ends up with significant if not total destruction and mass casualties. What happened here was nothing short of amazing and even miraculous. I saw the film Sully with my family last night, and I recommend that those who are interested in this historic incident, go and see it. Tom Hanks is superb. And if you do go, watch the credits at the end. You must stay. Some in Camberley Vue left too early and missed finale with the credits. I say no more.
